ass="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001117716"><div class="is-lead-inset"><div class="media-object scope-
          header
"><figure class="media-object-image img-header"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="860" height="574" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-831445?width=860&amp;height=574" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">软银首席执行官孙正义近日表示，他致力于人工智能领域。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：Kiyoshi Ota/彭博新闻</p></figcaption></figure></div></div></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001117716"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline">作者： <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/megumi-fujikawa" itemprop="url" rel="author">藤川惠</a></span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1">更新于 2023 年 8 月 8 日上午 7:48（东部时间） </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/softbank-posts-another-loss-despite-technology-share-rebound-703975d1"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><p>东京——<a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/JP/XTKS/9984" class="company-name">软银集团</a>公布了一年半以来的首次投资收益，并表示将谨慎推进<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/he-spent-140-billion-on-ai-with-little-to-show-now-he-is-trying-again-dbcca17?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">人工智能相关领域的</a>新投资。</p><p>这家日本科技投资者报告称，其旗舰愿景基金部门在 4 月至 6 月这个季度获得了 10 亿美元的投资收益，首席财务官后藤义光 (Yoshimitsu Goto) 表示，这一结果鼓励该公司寻找新的资金存放处。</p><p>后藤在新闻发布会上谈到最近<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/tech-stocks-meme-stocks-crypto-investors-are-feeling-bold-again-f158812b?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">科技股的反弹时表示，“我希望科技创业领域的</a>潮流正在扭转”。</p><p>该公司表示，其愿景基金 1、愿景基金 2 和拉丁美洲基金中价值在最近一个季度增长的公司数量比上一季度几乎翻了一番，这是市场状况改善的迹象。</p><p> <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/the-ai-frenzy-resurrects-the-old-softbank-1bca01f7?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">愿景基金部门本季度的投资</a>额为 18 亿美元，而前三个季度每个季度的投资额为 5 亿美元。这是该部门六个季度以来首次实现盈利。</p><p>总体而言，软银报告截至 6 月 30 日的季度净亏损 4776 亿日元，约合 33 亿美元。日元疲软导致该公司以美元计价的债务膨胀，而芯片设计公司 Arm 的收入因半导体行业放缓而下降。</p><p>在其持有的股票受到利率上升和<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/softbank-loses-nearly-6-billion-in-quarter-as-investments-suffer-11675752219?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">全球科技股抛售的</a>严重打击后，该公司一直对进行新投资持谨慎态度。为了保留现金，它于今年早些时候完成了对中国电子商务公司<a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/BABA" class="company-name">阿里巴巴集团控股</a>公司股份的<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/softbank-turns-big-seller-after-tech-rout-b816b988?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">出售</a>。 </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><div class="media-object-video"><div class="wsj-media-summary clearfix"><div class="strap-container"><h4 class="strap" itemprop="description"></h4></div></div><iframe width="400" height="225" src="https://video-api.wsj.com/api-video/player/v3/iframe.html?guid=E8DCC2B0-F066-41EA-9053-96EC3A35B05E&amp;height=225&amp;width=400&amp;plid=video_amp&amp;chainVideos=true&amp;parentUrl=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.wsj.com%2Famp%2Farticles%2Fsoftbank-posts-another-loss-despite-technology-share-rebound-703975d1&amp;a=a" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe><p class="imageCaption">芯片制造商英伟达跻身市值 1 万亿美元的公司专属俱乐部。 《华尔街日报》的 Asa Fitch 详细分析了 Nvidia 是如何实现这一目标的，以及人工智能为何推动该公司快速增长。插图：赵安妮<span class="imageCredit">
        
        
        </span></p></div></div><p>但随着科技行业的复苏，软银表示已准备好发起攻势，特别是在人工智能领域的投资。</p><p>周二，愿景基金首席执行官 Navneet Govil</p>表示Vision Fund 2仍有约80亿美元用于新投资。<p></p><p>首席执行官孙正义 (Masayoshi Son) 在 6 月份的公司年会上告诉股东，他<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/softbanks-masayoshi-son-says-hes-focusing-on-ai-inventions-621089ac?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">致力于人工智能</a>并经常通过与人工智能聊天机器人 ChatGPT 交谈来进行自己的发明。</p><p>后藤表示，软银在选择新投资时会更严格地关注其人工智能技术，因为有些人怀疑软银现有的投资是否真正以人工智能为中心。 Vision Fund 最近的一项投资是与英国初创公司 Tractable 达成的一项交易，该公司帮助保险公司使用人工智能处理索赔。</p><p>后藤表示<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/is-softbank-an-ai-stock-now-6e8dbfc7?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">，芯片设计公司 Arm</a>在美国上市的准备工作正在进行中，很快就会发布公告，但拒绝提供更多细节。 </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          inline
"><iframe width="300" height="300" src="https://graphics.wsj.com/dynamic-inset-iframer/?url=https://asset.wsj.net/wsjnewsgraphics/projects/narrator/d90969df-db3f-4890-9f4e-2892f502493a.json" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe></div><p>写信给藤川惠<a href="mailto:megumi.fujikawa@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">megumi.fujikawa@wsj.com</a></p></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Tue, 08 Aug 2023 11:48:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/softbank-posts-another-loss-尽管-technology-share-rebound-703975d1</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/softbank-posts-another-loss-尽管-technology-share-rebound-703975d1<author><![CDATA[Megumi Fujikawa]]></author><category> WSJ公司</category><category>人工智能技术</category><category>电信服务</category><category>无线电信服务</category><category>移动通讯</category><category>技术</category><category>财务绩效</category><category>收益</category><category>销售数据</category><category>企业/行业新闻</category><category>政治/一般新闻</category><category>计算机科学</category><category>科学/人文</category><category>内容类型</category><category>法激活过滤器</category><category>会展行业新闻过滤器</category><category>SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category>软银集团</category><category>9984.TO</category><category>日元：9984</category><category>后藤义光</category><category>财务绩效</category><category>收益</category><category>销售数据</category><category>公司的</category><category>行业新闻</category><category>政治的</category><category>一般新闻</category><category>计算机科学</category><category>科学</category><category>人文学科</category><category>内容类型</category><category>法蒂瓦过滤器</category><category>会展行业新闻过滤器</category><category>人工智能技术</category><category>电信服务</category><category>无线电信服务</category><category>移动电信</category><category>技术</category></item><item><title><![CDATA[China Drafts Rules for Facial-Recognition Use]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div>当局对何时使用此类技术提出了限制，即使他们保留了国家安全例外情况<!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001117836"><div class="is-lead-inset"><div class="media-object scope-
          header
"><figure class="media-object-image img-header"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="860" height="573" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-831488?width=860&amp;height=573" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">近年来，面部识别在中国的使用不断扩大。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：Qilai Shen/彭博新闻</p></figcaption></figure></div></div></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001117836"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline"> <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/karen-hao" itemprop="url" rel="author">郝凯伦</a></span>和<span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/liza-lin" itemprop="url" rel="author">林丽莎</a></span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1">美国东部时间 2023 年 8 月 8 日上午 7:07 </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/china-drafts-rules-for-facial-recognition-use-4953506e"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><p>中国周二发布了限制面部识别使用的规则草案，采取措施限制极化技术的扩张，同时为国家安全相关用途留出大量空间。</p><p>互联网监管机构中国网络安全管理局的草案建议将该技术的使用限制在具有特定目的且足够必要的情况下。这些规则还禁止使用该技术来识别种族、民族、宗教信仰或健康状况——未经科学证明的应用——除非得到个人同意或出于国家安全的目的。</p><p>这些规定使中国对面部识别的私人和商业用途的立场更接近西方规范，包括欧盟和美国地方政府提出的规则。它还为与国家安全相关的技术使用留出了例外情况，这是一个共同特点中国的数据和安全法规。</p><p>耶鲁大学法学院蔡英文中国中心高级研究员萨姆·萨克斯 (Samm Sacks) 表示：“在一项法律中，有一些条款反映了一个由技术驱动的独裁超级大国，也反映出对技术滥用的真正担忧。” “这就是中国治理方式的酸甜苦辣。”</p><p>该提案是中国政府采取的一系列举措中的最新举措，旨在限制企业使用数据和人工智能的方式，使其处于全球监管尖端技术的最前沿。 <strong>&nbsp;</strong></p><p>今年早些时候，监管机构对所谓的 Deepfakes、人工智能生成媒体<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/china-a-pioneer-in-regulating-algorithms-turns-its-focus-to-deepfakes-11673149283?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">实施了规则</a>，并<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/china-lays-out-strict-rules-for-chatgpt-like-ai-tools-32f70c89?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">提出了与 OpenAI 的 ChatGPT 类似的生成人工智能工具的其他</a>规则。去年，它开始<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/china-blazes-hazy-new-trail-to-tame-internets-algorithms-11661866321?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">监管流行应用程序和互联网平台的算法</a>，包括 TikTok 的中文版抖音和无处不在的超级应用程序<a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/TCEHY" class="">微信</a><span class="company-name-type">。</span></p><p>尽管包括马萨诸塞州在内的一些州和旧金山等城市，但美国没有规范面部识别使用的国家法律<strong>&nbsp;</strong>施加了限制，特别是在执法部门使用该技术方面。在欧洲，政策制定者最近就人工智能法律草案达成一致，该草案将禁止警察和其他国家安全部队在公共场所使用实时面部识别。</p><p>中国的规定也是在中国的新冠疫情控制导致全面采用位置记录和访问控制技术之后出台的。</p><p>研究学者格雷厄姆·韦伯斯特（Graham Webster）是斯坦福大学数字中国项目的负责人，该项目负责研究中国的数字政策发展，他表示，该草案似乎旨在阻止不必要地使用面部识别。他说：“如果得到执行，它将冷却生物识别设备在安全环境之外的扩散。”</p><p>过去七年里，面部识别技术在中国的使用一直在蓬勃发展，使用面部作为身份识别形式的方式在商场、办公楼、机场和酒店如雨后春笋般涌现。中国消费者可以选择在一些商店使用刷脸支付、进入建筑物以及在登机前进行身份检查。 </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="466" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-831490?width=700&amp;height=466" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">中国已开始监管支撑流行应用程序（例如 TikTok 的中文版抖音）的算法。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：Andrea Verdelli/彭博新闻</p></figcaption></figure></div><p>监控摄像头在中国许多城市随处可见，中国一些最大的面部识别供应商与当地警方建立了合作伙伴关系，提供用于安全目的的技术——不仅追踪罪犯，还追踪异见人士、少数民族和政府认为威胁国家安全的其他人。</p><p>这种技术是国际社会批评北京对待西北地区新疆少数民族群体的批评的核心。中国政府在该地区对突厥裔穆斯林开展了强制民族同化运动。研究人员称，新疆当局使用面部识别和其他监控工具来追踪和分类穆斯林，将数十万人送往拘留营接受政治洗脑。中国否认了这些指控，称其在新疆的政策是为了防止恐怖主义。</p><p>许多中国人或热情或冷漠地迎接智能相机的首次推出，并在日常生活中采用了这项技术。尽管如此，中国领导人对面部识别的广泛使用越来越不满。</p><p> <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/chinese-professor-files-rare-lawsuit-over-use-of-facial-recognition-technology-11572884626?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">在 2019 年罕见的针对该技术的诉讼中</a>，中国法学教授郭兵指控沿海城市杭州的一家动物园要求他使用面部识别系统才能进入动物园，从而侵犯了他的消费者权利，并且当他不服从时阻止他。法院命令动物园向郭支付赔偿金并删除他的数据，但没有提及动物园继续强制游客进行面部识别是否合法。</p><p>中国南方智库南都个人信息保护研究中心对2019年公众对面部识别的态度进行的调查也发现，普通中国人越来越担心由于缺乏数据安全而导致个人信息被泄露。</p><p>周二拟议的法规将分散在中国各项法律中的对人脸识别技术使用的限制整合到一个框架中，其中包括 2021 年<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/china-set-to-pass-one-of-the-worlds-strictest-data-privacy-laws-11629201927?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">通过的国家隐私法</a>。未经同意即可收集和使用，重申了中国 2017 年《网络安全法》的一个关键方面，即收集个人数据时需要征得个人同意。</p><p>韦伯斯特说，这种冗余的一部分是实用的：明确现有法律应如何应用于面部识别环境。萨克斯说，北京方面还通过这些规则表明它意识到公众的担忧。 </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="466" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-831492?width=700&amp;height=466" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">在中国，面部识别可用于商场、写字楼、机场和酒店的身份识别。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：Andy Wong/美联社</p></figcaption></figure></div><p>该法规中的一些条款涉及到一些细节，例如，规定不得在酒店房间、浴室或厕所等场所使用面部识别技术，而公众此前曾强烈<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/facial-recognition-goes-mainstream-1537322700" target="_blank" class="icon none">反对在这些地方使用该技术</a>。它还禁止实体迫使个人采用人脸识别的行为（例如动物园的情况）作为确定其身份的方法。</p><p>与此同时，中国在领导人习近平的领导下一直在扩大国家安全的定义，以涵盖任何被视为破坏共产党统治的事物，习近平为中国可能<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/china-congress-xi-jinping-us-11665753002" target="_blank" class="icon none">与西方的对抗</a>做好了准备。 7月，修订并收紧的<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/chinas-expanded-spy-law-adds-to-chilling-effect-of-detentions-ce8cea1a?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">反间谍法</a>生效，引起了外国政府和企业的担忧。</p><p>拟议的法规是当局在承认公众辩论和保持对国家安全的严格控制之间游走的最新努力。萨克斯说：“它允许政府通过向公众展示他们正在做出反应来释放压力阀，同时也可以转移对中央当局使用这些技术的注意力。”</p><p>写信给凯伦·豪<a href="mailto:karen.hao@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">（karen.hao@wsj.com）</a>和丽莎·林（ <a href="mailto:liza.lin@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">liza.lin@wsj.com</a> ）</p></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Tue, 08 Aug 2023 11:07:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/china-drafts-rules-for-facial-recognition-use-4953506e</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/china-drafts-rules-for-facial-recognition-use-4953506e<author><![CDATA[Karen HaoLiza Lin]]></author><category>法规/政府政策</category><category>企业/行业新闻</category><category>人工智能/机器学习</category><category>政治/一般新闻</category><category>国家/公共安全</category><category>计算机科学</category><category>科学/人文</category><category>国家安全措施/政策</category><category>内容类型</category><category>法激活过滤器</category><category>会展行业新闻过滤器</category><category>SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category>规定</category><category>政府政策</category><category>公司的</category><category>行业新闻</category><category>人工智能</category><category>机器学习</category><category>政治的</category><category>一般新闻</category><category>国家的</category><category>公安</category><category>计算机科学</category><category>科学</category><category>人文学科</category><category>国家安全措施</category><category>政策</category><category>内容类型</category><category>法蒂瓦过滤器</category><category>会展行业新闻过滤器</category></item><item><title><![CDATA[Elon Musk Calls Cybertruck Tesla’s ‘Best Product Ever.’ Here Comes the Test.]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div>卡车预计将于年底上市，比原计划晚两年<!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001116905"><div class="is-lead-inset"><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><div class="media-object-video"><div class="wsj-media-summary clearfix"><div class="strap-container"><h4 class="strap" itemprop="description"></h4></div></div><iframe width="400" height="225" src="https://video-api.wsj.com/api-video/player/v3/iframe.html?guid=B1A79903-5C46-4C69-8AC4-A0082045E182&amp;height=225&amp;width=400&amp;plid=video_amp&amp;chainVideos=true&amp;parentUrl=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.wsj.com%2Famp%2Farticles%2Felon-musk-calls-cybertruck-teslas-best-product-ever-here-comes-the-test-42095f45&amp;a=a" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe><p class="imageCaption">特斯拉 Cyber​​truck 的推出是历史上最受期待的电动汽车发布之一。巴克莱分析师 Dan Levy 和 AlixPartners 的 Mark Wakefield 探讨了特斯拉首款皮卡将如何撼动皮卡市场。照片：弗雷德里克·布朗/盖蒂图片社<span class="imageCredit">
        
        
        </span></p></div></div></div></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001116905"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline"> <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/rebecca-elliott" itemprop="url" rel="author">丽贝卡·埃利奥特</a></span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1">美国东部时间 2023 年 8 月 8 日上午 5:30 </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/elon-musk-calls-cybertruck-teslas-best-product-ever-here-comes-the-test-42095f45"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><p><a href="https://www.wsj.com/topics/person/elon-musk">埃隆·马斯克 (Elon Musk)</a>正在寻求用 Cyber​​truck 重新构想经典的美国皮卡，这是一款外观独特的卡车，采用全角度和未上漆的不锈钢材质。</p><p>现在，<a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/TSLA" class="company-name">特斯拉</a>预计将在今年年底推出这款卡车，接下来的几个月将考验他是否能够执行这一愿景并交付该公司三年多来的第一辆新型乘用车。</p><p>事实证明，将 Cyber​​truck 推向市场已经充满挑战，多年来的延误包括设计变更、成本超支和流行病的不确定性。最新的转折发生在周一，这家电动汽车制造商宣布首席财务官扎克·柯克霍恩(Zach Kirkhorn) <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/tesla-finance-chief-zach-kirkhorn-steps-down-44e00ad?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">辞职</a>，他在保持公司成本稳定方面发挥了重要作用。</p><p>这款电动卡车的设计打破了传统皮卡的模式，具有三角形轮廓和<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/tesla-unveiled-a-bullet-proof-pickup-then-the-window-broke-11574444427?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">防弹车身</a>。一些行业观察人士担心，这种设计独特的汽车对买家的吸引力有限，而且由于利润<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/tesla-tsla-q2-earnings-report-2023-9be2b571?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">已经受到压力，</a>开始生产的成本将损害盈利能力。</p><p>投资者押注这款卡车值得等待，并且它将为特斯拉品牌注入新的活力，该品牌的产品线比许多竞争对手都更老。</p><p>特斯拉投资者、未来基金管理合伙人加里·布莱克 (Gary Black) 表示：“Cyber​​truck 非常与众不同，它将让整个系列充满活力。”</p><p> Musk has been hyping the truck for years. He has called it the company&#39;s “best product ever” and has pitched the vehicle as a “badass, futuristic armored personnel carrier” that accelerates like a sports car and is packed with new technology. </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="466" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-831285?width=700&amp;height=466" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> Tesla has taken on manufacturing challenges with the Cybertruck, which uses stronger, heavier stainless steel instead of the sheet metal typically used in car bodies.</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: Robyn Beck/Agence France-Presse/Getty Images</p></figcaption></figure></div><p> In April, Musk said Tesla likely would begin <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/tesla-tsla-q1-earnings-report-2023-6b441d30?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">delivering the new pickups</a> in small numbers by the end of September. Output is expected to climb in 2024.</p><p> During the company&#39;s most recent call with Wall Street analysts, however, Musk sidestepped a question about pricing and delivery schedules. Instead, he said deliveries would come this year. He also echoed past warnings that beginning production of a new vehicle can be tricky.</p><p> “The production ramp will move as fast as the slowest and least lucky elements of the entire supply chain and internal production,” Musk said last month.</p><p> Tesla didn&#39;t respond to requests for comment.</p><p> Ramping up production of new vehicles has bedeviled Tesla, where Musk has described the launch of the Model 3 sedan several years ago as “production hell” that nearly killed the company.</p><p> Originally expected in 2021, the Cybertruck began to face challenges almost as soon as it was first shown in November 2019.</p><p> Within months, the Covid-19 pandemic was wreaking havoc on global supply chains and the Cybertruck took a back seat to surer bets designed to <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/tesla-tsla-q4-earnings-report-2021-11643162910?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">quickly expand Tesla&#39;s market share</a> or <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/tesla-to-introduce-upgraded-model-s-to-jump-start-high-end-model-sales-11623334024?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">pad the bottom line</a> , people familiar with the matter said.</p><p> Later, as employees turned their attention to the Cybertruck, they struggled to deliver on their boss&#39;s promises while keeping a lid on costs. </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="412" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-831286?width=700&amp;height=412" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> A Model Y on the factory floor at Tesla&#39;s &#39;Cyber Rodeo&#39; marking the opening last year of the company&#39;s factory outside of Austin, Texas.</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: Jay Janner/Associated Press</p></figcaption></figure></div><p> “You can make something infinitely desirable, but if it&#39;s not affordable, that will constrain people&#39;s ability to buy it because they don&#39;t have the money,” Musk said in January 2022, adding that he worried about making a truck that was within reach for Tesla&#39;s customers.</p><p> He initially promised <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/tesla-targets-u-s-auto-makers-profit-engine-with-electric-pickup-11574341200?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">three tiers of the truck</a> , starting with a $39,900 entry-level model and topping out at a higher-end version starting at $69,900. He has since said the pricing and specs would be different, citing inflation and “various issues” without sharing specifics.</p><p> The company has taken on an array of new manufacturing challenges with the Cybertruck, which uses stronger, heavier stainless steel instead of the sheet metal typically used in car bodies.</p><p> Tesla aimed to skip an expensive manufacturing step for the outer shell of the truck with stainless steel, which doesn&#39;t need to be painted because it is corrosion-resistant. However, it is rarely used to form vehicle bodies in part because it is less malleable than traditional materials. (DeLorean Motor&#39;s stainless-steel-bodied sports car was featured as the time machine in the “Back to the Future” films.)</p><p> “There&#39;s not industrywide knowledge of how to build stainless steel vehicles, and so there&#39;s a whole bunch of things nobody knows about that they&#39;re going to encounter,” said Doug Betts, president of JD Power&#39;s automotive division.</p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          wrap
"></div><p> And while Tesla excels in areas such as software and powertrain development, it has struggled with the process of building the car body, something the Cybertruck is likely to test, Betts said.</p><p> In addition to reimagining how pickup trucks should look, Musk wanted to upend how they are assembled. He envisioned a vehicle whose outer walls provide much of the overall structure.</p><p> “We moved the mass to the outside. We created an exoskeleton,” Musk said at the 2019 reveal.</p><p> However, Tesla has scaled back its exoskeleton ambitions, pursuing a more traditional vehicle design with an interior structure, people familiar with the matter said. The company did so, at least in part, to meet safety standards, one of the people said.</p><p> Some auto observers had expected more.</p><p> “It&#39;s unconventional in some areas, but for the most part it&#39;s a conventional build,” said Sandy Munro, an engineering consultant who tears apart cars and has reviewed pictures of early versions of the Cybertruck. “It&#39;s not the dramatic change that I was looking forward to,” he said, adding that he still thinks the vehicle will “take the market by storm.”</p><p> Musk has said he expects to make 250,000 or more Cybertrucks a year once output ramps up, making it a niche product in comparison to the company&#39;s best selling Model Y crossover. In total, Tesla sold about 1.3 million vehicles last year and is aiming to sell 20 million annually by 2030.</p><p> The Cybertruck&#39;s delays put it behind in a competitive segment where rivals have already brought their own EV pickups to market. <a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/F" class="">Ford Motor</a> <span class="company-name-type">&#39;s</span> F-150 Lightning, the top-selling electric pickup, starts at $49,995 after the company <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/ford-cuts-price-of-ev-f-150-lightning-truck-by-up-to-17-2cc21c6a?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">slashed prices last month</a> . Rivian Automotive&#39;s competitor, the R1T, starts at $73,000.</p><div class="media-object scope-web
          wrap
"><div class="media-object-rich-text"><h4>分享你的意见</h4><p><em>Do you think Tesla&#39;s Cybertruck will ultimately be successful? Why or why not?加入下面的对话。</em></p></div></div><p> Still, if Tesla can be successful, there is great potential. Full-size pickup trucks are the cash cow of the US auto industry, making up 13% of North American vehicle sales last year while being responsible for about 40% of profits, according to Wells Fargo.</p><p> Analysts expect early efforts to build Tesla&#39;s truck could further erode the company&#39;s profitability.</p><p> But the truck should eventually boost Tesla&#39;s profit margin if the company is able to deliver on its promises, said Anthony Wang, who co-leads the technology investing team at <a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/TROW" class="">T. Rowe Price Associates</a> <span class="company-name-type">,</span> one of the company&#39;s largest shareholders.</p><p> “Whether the ramp comes this quarter or next, it doesn&#39;t really matter,” Wang said. “What matters more is: Can they execute on the cost and the specs?”</p><p>写信给丽贝卡·埃利奥特（Rebecca Elliott）： <a href="mailto:rebecca.elliott@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">rebecca.elliott@wsj.com</a> </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          inline
"><iframe width="300" height="300" src="https://graphics.wsj.com/dynamic-inset-iframer/?url=https://asset.wsj.net/wsjnewsgraphics/projects/narrator/e1f7a12e-412d-41e7-b6c1-3f6c0615c7c1.json" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe></div></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Tue, 08 Aug 2023 09:30:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/elon-musk-calls-cybertruck-teslas-best-product-ever-here-comes-the-test-42095f45</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/elon-musk-calls-cybertruck-teslas-best-product-ever-here-comes-the-test-42095f45<author><![CDATA[Rebecca Elliott]]></author><category> WSJ公司</category><category>机动车</category><category>替代燃料汽车</category><category>汽车</category><category>企业/行业新闻</category><category>SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category>特斯拉</category><category>特斯拉</category><category>埃隆·马斯克</category><category>公司的</category><category>行业新闻</category><category>机动车</category><category>替代燃料汽车</category><category>汽车</category></item><item><title><![CDATA[The Legal Assault on Corporate Diversity Efforts Has Begun]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div> Conservative groups challenge Amazon, Comcast and others using many of the same tools that helped kill affirmative-action programs in colleges <figure><img src="https://images.wsj.net/im-831356/?width=1278&amp;size=1" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"><figcaption> Emil Lendof/The Wall Street Journal <span>Emil Lendof/The Wall Street Journal</span> </figcaption></figure><!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001116214"></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001116214"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline"> By <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/theo-francis" itemprop="url" rel="author">Theo Francis</a></span> and <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/lauren-weber" itemprop="url" rel="author">Lauren Weber</a></span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1"> Aug. 8, 2023 5:30 am ET </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/diversity-equity-dei-companies-blum-2040b173"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          bigtophero
"></div><p> Conservative legal activists <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/supreme-court-rules-against-affirmative-action-c94b5a9c?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">successfully challenged</a> the use of affirmative action by universities. Now they are going after diversity initiatives widely deployed across American corporations. Some companies are already reconsidering their efforts.</p><p> In lawsuits, shareholder letters and petitions to the Equal Employment Opportunity Commission, activists are using some of the same tactics that progressive groups have used to advance diversity, equity and inclusion, or DEI, programs. They are arguing that companies are violating rules against race- and sex-discrimination, including those drawn from legislation designed to secure the rights of Black Americans.</p><p> <a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/CMCSA" class="company-name">Comcast</a> settled a case accusing it of illegally favoring minority-owned small-business customers with grants and marketing advice. <a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/AMZN" class="company-name">Amazon</a> has been sued in Texas over a program offering an extra $10,000 to Black- or Latino-owned delivery-service contractors. <a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/SBUX" class="company-name">Starbucks</a> directors and executives are being sued by a shareholder arguing they violated their duty to investors by supporting diversity policies.</p><p> Dozens of corporate law firms and major employers have received letters from Republican officials warning them to adhere to laws prohibiting racial quotas and preferences in employment and contracting decisions.</p><p> Edward Blum, who also <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/affirmative-action-supreme-court-ed-blum-100b36c3" target="_blank" class="icon none">organized the challenge</a> that culminated in the US Supreme Court&#39;s decision to <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/supreme-court-rules-against-affirmative-action-c94b5a9c?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">overturn affirmative action</a> , used a recently formed nonprofit group to sue Georgia investment manager Fearless Fund, charging that a grant program for startups is discriminatory. Fearless makes early-stage investments in businesses run by women of color.</p><p> Companies say their initiatives fall within the law. Many say they remain committed to increasing the demographic diversity of their workforces and suppliers, citing <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/the-business-case-for-more-diversity-11572091200" target="_blank" class="icon none">business benefits</a> and the hurdles some groups continue to face in American corporations.</p><p> Privately, <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/companiesexpectnew-challenges-todiversitypolicies-after-court-ruling-4bf48c1d" target="_blank" class="icon none">many are asking their lawyers</a> if and how much they should modify their methods in light of the affirmative-action decision. </p><div class="media-object scope-
          bleed
"><figure class="media-object-image img-bleed"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="1260" height="841" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-828205?width=1260&amp;height=841" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> A federal lawsuit against Amazon.com targets a program awarding an additional $10,000 to Black, Latino and Native American delivery-service contractors to defray startup costs.</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: Kathy Tran/Bloomberg News</p></figcaption></figure></div><p> Many of the legal efforts against corporate diversity programs predate the high court&#39;s June 29 decision. That ruling, centered squarely on higher-education admissions, didn&#39;t address employment or business practices.</p><p> But it added momentum to an effort by conservative activists and public officials to challenge corporate diversity programs. Companies have long relied on rationales similar to those buttressing affirmative action at universities—that there are benefits to diversity. By dismissing that rationale, the high court weakened the justification for other programs that promote it.</p><p> “Anything a company&#39;s doing that is treating someone differently because of their race, even if it&#39;s a small part of the decision-making process, is going to be scrutinized,” said Dan Lennington, a former Wisconsin deputy solicitor general and deputy counsel for Wisconsin Institute for Law and Liberty, the legal group behind the Comcast lawsuit.</p><p> Employment lawyers say it is likely a matter of time before one of these cases reaches the Supreme Court. Some companies have decided they aren&#39;t going to wait for the court to weigh in. That is especially true for programs that were quickly adopted after the May 2020 killing of George Floyd in police custody, said Angela Berg, who led the global DEI practice at HR consulting firm Mercer and now consults independently.</p><p> Some executives “were uncomfortable with equity programs from the get-go,” said Berg, referring to initiatives such as mentorship or training programs. The Supreme Court has changed the risk calculation, she said.</p><p> Companies are evaluating diversity programs in light of litigation threats that often seem designed to stoke public fear, said Fordham University law professor Atinuke Adediran. She has received inquiries on the subject from an association of human-resources officers at large companies. “Most of what the firms are doing for diversity is legal,” she said. “Companies may need to be ready to defend themselves.”</p><h3> <strong>A Civil War weapon</strong></h3><p> Cable giant Comcast limited a small-business grant program to companies at least 51% owned and operated by someone identifying as Black, indigenous, a person of color, or female—people the company said had been disproportionately affected by the coronavirus pandemic.</p><p> The Wisconsin Institute for Law and Liberty, in suing Comcast in April 2022, cited the 1866 Civil Rights Act. One provision often referred to as Section 1981 says all Americans should have the same rights to sue and enforce contracts “as is enjoyed by white citizens.” The Wisconsin Institute, which says it supports litigation promoting “individual initiative and ordered liberty that leads to prosperity,” essentially turned that section on its head by gathering several white, male business owners as plaintiffs. </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="503" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-831273?width=700&amp;height=503" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> Some activists cite a Civil War-era law that says all Americans should have the same rights to sue and enforce contracts &#39;as is enjoyed by white citizens.&#39; Pictured is a sketch by F. Dielman showing a celebration of the abolition of slavery in the District of Columbia, April 1866.</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: Library of Congress</p></figcaption></figure></div><p> In mid-September, when Comcast announced the next round of grants, it <a href="https://corporate.comcast.com/press/releases/comcast-rise-investment-fund-grants-small-businesses-covid-19-pandemic)" target="_blank" class="icon none">opened the program</a> to all small businesses. Two months later, Comcast settled the litigation.</p><p> A Comcast spokesman declined to comment. In a news release about the program in May, Comcast described the program as evolving “from helping businesses survive the pandemic, to helping businesses and their communities thrive with a focus on economic growth.”</p><p> A federal lawsuit against Amazon.com filed outside Dallas in July 2022 also invokes the 1866 law. It targets a program awarding an additional $10,000 to Black, Latino and Native American delivery-service contractors to defray startup costs. The lawsuit also criticizes an Amazon program aimed at helping Black-owned businesses sell products on Amazon&#39;s website.</p><p> The plaintiff, a Denton County, Texas, resident, wants to apply to start an Amazon delivery-service contractor, but says she won&#39;t until the company eliminates the assistance for minority contractors or offers whites and Asians the same benefit, the complaint says. The plaintiff can&#39;t apply to become an Amazon delivery service partner “without subjecting herself to racial discrimination,” the lawsuit says.</p><p> The case seeks class-action status. It was filed by attorneys including the general counsel of America First Legal, a Washington, DC, nonprofit headed by former Trump administration adviser Stephen Miller. America First Legal describes itself as combating “an unholy alliance of corrupt special interests, big tech titans, the fake news media, and liberal Washington politicians.”</p><p> Amazon has moved to dismiss the lawsuit, saying its selection process for delivery contractors is race-neutral and that the plaintiff doesn&#39;t have standing to sue because she hasn&#39;t applied to be an Amazon contractor.</p><p> In court filings, the company calls her complaint “the epitome of an abstract and generalized grievance by a member of the general population about an internal corporate program that has no actual effect on her.”</p><p> Amazon declined to comment on the lawsuit. “We believe in the importance of diversity, equity, and inclusion,” a spokesman said in a written statement. “We&#39;ll investigate the potential impact of any legal decisions on our programs and adjust as necessary to comply with the law.”</p><h3> <strong>The workplace discrimination argument</strong></h3><p> Title VII of the Civil Rights Act of 1964 bans workplace discrimination. The recent affirmative-action decision didn&#39;t address employment practices directly. But Supreme Court Justice Neil Gorsuch in a concurring opinion noted “materially identical language” on discrimination in the laws governing higher education and employment.</p><p> Starbucks officers and directors were sued in August 2022 by National Center for Public Policy Research, a conservative think tank that owns 56 shares in the coffee chain. It accuses Starbucks of violating Title VII and Section 1981, and the officials of breaching their fiduciary duty to shareholders by embracing policies it says violate antidiscrimination law in areas including employment, supplier contracts and executive compensation.</p><p> Under the policies, Starbucks says it wants at least 30% of its workforce at all levels to be Black, indigenous or people of color by 2025. It plans to implement an analytics tool that lets managers see their progress and uses workforce diversity measures to help set executive pay.</p><p> Starbucks and company officials are seeking to dismiss the case, with a hearing scheduled for Friday. They say NCPPR hasn&#39;t shown any real harm from the policies, which are covered by a legal principle that gives company officials broad discretion in running their business, and that courts have upheld diversity policies as permissible. Abandoning them would leave Starbucks vulnerable to other litigation, they say. </p><div class="media-object scope-
          bleed
"><figure class="media-object-image img-bleed"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="1260" height="884" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-828201?width=1260&amp;height=884" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> Starbucks officers and directors were sued last year over policies that involve increasing workforce diversity at all levels of the coffee chain.</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: Mario Tama/Getty Images</p></figcaption></figure></div><p> “We remain committed to creating a culture of warmth and belonging, where everyone is welcome,” a company spokeswoman said.</p><p> In court, Starbucks and its officials also argue NCPPR doesn&#39;t represent shareholders, who have rejected previous proxy proposals from the group suggesting Starbucks favors liberal or “woke” perspectives.</p><p> <a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/KO" class="company-name">Coca-Cola</a> is among the companies that has already backtracked. In early 2021, then-General Counsel Bradley Gayton addressed a letter to outside law firms saying that 30% of new legal work for the soda giant should be performed by lawyers who are women, LGBTQ+, disabled or members of racial and ethnic minority groups. Law firms had to report demographic data to Coke, which could cut their fees if the guidelines weren&#39;t met, the letter said. Gayton stepped down from the role three months later.</p><p> American Civil Rights Project, a nonprofit law firm that also represents NCPPR in its Starbucks lawsuit, threatened to sue Coke on behalf of shareholders. In a letter to the company that June, the group called the policies “textbook violations” of Section 1981.</p><p> In early 2022 Gayton&#39;s successor, Monica Howard Doublas, wrote to the American Civil Rights Project that while the company remained fully committed to advancing DEI in the legal profession, she had contacted law firms to tell them the guidelines were never company policy.</p><h3> <strong>A chilling effect</strong></h3><p> America First Legal Foundation, the group backing the Texas lawsuit against Amazon, has written to the Equal Employment Opportunity Commission, urging the four current commissioners to bypass the usual complaint process and open investigations into diversity practices at a range of brand-name companies.</p><p> Andrea Lucas, who was nominated to the commission by President Trump, declined to comment on the likelihood that she or other commissioners would open investigations. She said she sees “significant legal and practical risk” in many corporate diversity programs. “Equal opportunity is our charge,” she said of the agency&#39;s mission, “but the law does not demand equal outcomes.” </p><div class="media-object scope-
          wrap
"><figure class="media-object-image img-wrap"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="639" height="639" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-830072?width=639&amp;height=639" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> Bradley Gayton, former general counsel at Coca-Cola, announced new guidelines for the makeup of attorneys doing legal work for the soda giant.</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: Coca-Cola/Business Wire</p></figcaption></figure></div><p> Civil-rights lawyers say conservative activists&#39; arguments distort the original purpose of laws designed to protect groups that, historically, have had fewer labor-market opportunities or difficulty cracking corporate ceilings.</p><p> “The intent here is more political gain and a chilling effect—unfortunately it&#39;s effective,” said Katy Youker, an attorney with the Lawyers&#39; Committee for Civil Rights Under Law, which has been tracking challenges to corporate programs.</p><p> In Florida, a federal judge last year halted enforcement of provisions in HB 7, better known as the Stop Woke Act, which would have restricted private employers from conducting some diversity-related training. The judge said the measures violated companies&#39; free speech rights. Gov. <a href="https://www.wsj.com/topics/person/ron-desantis">Ron DeSantis</a> &#39;s administration has appealed the decision.</p><p> The pressure leaves employers vulnerable to litigation for either going too far or not far enough in addressing barriers to equity and inclusion, lawyers say.</p><p> “Employers still have obligations to comply with civil rights statutes,” said Charles McLaurin, senior counsel with the NAACP Legal Defense and Educational Fund. Rolling back DEI programs designed to expand workplace opportunities, he added, “has the potential of creating a hostile environment for certain marginalized groups. Companies would still face exposure.”</p><p> Write to Theo Francis at <a href="mailto:theo.francis@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">theo.francis@wsj.com</a> and Lauren Weber at <a href="mailto:Lauren.Weber@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">Lauren.Weber@wsj.com</a> </p><div class="media-object scope-
          bleed
"><figure class="media-object-image img-bleed"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="1260" height="840" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-828197?width=1260&amp;height=840" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> The administration of Florida Gov. Ron DeSantis appealed a federal judge&#39;s decision to halt enforcement of elements of what is known as the Stop Woke Act.</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: Daniel A. Varela/Miami Herald/Associated Press</p></figcaption></figure></div></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Tue, 08 Aug 2023 09:30:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/diversity-equity-dei-companies-blum-2040b173</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/diversity-equity-dei-companies-blum-2040b173<author><![CDATA[Theo FrancisLauren Weber]]></author><category> WSJ公司</category><category>wsjillustration</category><category>领导者</category><category>Broadcasting</category><category> Cable Broadcasting</category><category>媒体/娱乐</category><category>Corporate Crime/Legal Action</category><category>法规/政府政策</category><category>劳工/人事</category><category>企业/行业新闻</category><category>Workplace Discrimination/Abuse</category><category> Affirmative Action</category><category>政治/一般新闻</category><category>社会/社区</category><category>犯罪/法律诉讼</category><category>歧视</category><category>教育</category><category>人权/公民自由</category><category>社会问题</category><category>University/College</category><category>内容类型</category><category>法激活过滤器</category><category>C&amp;E 行政新闻过滤器</category><category>会展行业新闻过滤器</category><category>SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category> corporate crime</category><category>合法举动</category><category>规定</category><category>政府政策</category><category>劳动</category><category>人员</category><category>公司的</category><category>行业新闻</category><category>workplace discrimination</category><category>虐待</category><category>affirmative action</category><category>政治的</category><category>一般新闻</category><category>社会</category><category>社区</category><category>犯罪</category><category>歧视</category><category>教育</category><category>人权</category><category>公民权利</category><category>社会问题</category><category>university</category><category> college</category><category>内容类型</category><category>法蒂瓦过滤器</category><category>C&amp;E 行政新闻过滤器</category><category>会展行业新闻过滤器</category><category>broadcasting</category><category> cable broadcasting</category><category>媒体</category><category>娱乐</category></item><item><title><![CDATA[Tesla CFO Zach Kirkhorn Steps Down Ahead of Cybertruck Launch]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div>公司资深人士被视为埃隆·马斯克(Elon Musk)首席执行官的可能继任者<!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001115434"><div class="is-lead-inset"><div class="media-object scope-
          header
"><figure class="media-object-image img-header"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="860" height="484" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-830811?width=860&amp;height=484" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">扎克·柯克霍恩（左）和埃隆·马斯克在今年的特斯拉投资者日。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：特斯拉</p></figcaption></figure></div></div></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001115434"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline"> <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/rebecca-elliott" itemprop="url" rel="author">丽贝卡·埃利奥特</a></span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1">Updated Aug. 7, 2023 5:56 pm ET </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/tesla-finance-chief-zach-kirkhorn-steps-down-44e00ad"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><p><a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/TSLA" class="company-name">特斯拉</a>首席财务官扎克·科克霍恩 (Zach Kirkhorn) 在担任该职位四年多后辞职，他在幕后工作，将<a href="https://www.wsj.com/topics/person/elon-musk">埃隆·马斯克 (Elon Musk</a> ) 的雄心壮志变为现实。</p><p> The electric-car maker on Monday said Chief Accounting Officer Vaibhav Taneja had been appointed as CFO on Aug. 4, when the 38-year-old Kirkhorn left the position.</p><p>他的这一出人意料的举动是在特斯拉的 Cyber​​truck 皮卡今年晚些时候上市之前做出的，这引发了人们对马斯克继任计划的质疑。马斯克现年 52 岁，经营着多家公司，包括 SpaceX 和 X（前身为 Twitter）社交媒体平台。</p><p>据《华尔街日报》5 月份报道，特斯拉没有明确的第二把手，但<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/tesla-executive-elon-musk-cfo-zach-kirkhorn-b1998ae7?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">董事会成员曾讨论过</a>柯克霍恩可能接替马斯克担任首席执行官。</p><p> Shares were down around 2% in early-afternoon trading.周末，马斯克表示他可能需要进行<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/elon-musk-surgery-mark-zuckerberg-fight-3598da84?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">更多颈部手术</a>。 </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><div class="media-object-video"><div class="wsj-media-summary clearfix"><div class="strap-container"><h4 class="strap" itemprop="description"></h4></div></div><iframe width="400" height="225" src="https://video-api.wsj.com/api-video/player/v3/iframe.html?guid=5CFE9E1C-85FE-4D55-A214-0EAAA6F54763&amp;height=225&amp;width=400&amp;plid=video_amp&amp;chainVideos=true&amp;parentUrl=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.wsj.com%2Famp%2Farticles%2Ftesla-finance-chief-zach-kirkhorn-steps-down-44e00ad&amp;a=a" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe><p class="imageCaption"> 7 月下旬，埃隆·马斯克将 Twitter 的名称改为 X，这是该品牌的重大变化。但这并不是这位科技亿万富翁第一次使用 URL x.com。 《华尔街日报》解释了该网站的过去可能预示着其未来。<span class="imageCredit">
        
        
        </span></p></div></div><p>科克霍恩的离职是在特斯拉高层经历了一段相对平稳的时期之后发生的，在其 20 年的历史中，这段时期经历了巨大的人员流动，尤其是在新车发布期间。 Dozens of senior executives, for example, <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/elon-musk-races-to-exit-teslas-production-hell-1530149814?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none" rel="noreferrer noopener">departed ahead of</a> or during the company&#39;s difficult introduction of the Model 3 sedan.</p><p> The EV maker is preparing to deliver its first new passenger vehicle in more than three years, the Cybertruck, and is building out manufacturing capabilities as it seeks to become the world&#39;s biggest car company by volume.</p><p> Kirkhorn, who joined the automaker in 2010, helped transform Tesla into the world&#39;s most valuable carmaker and a profit machine that has delivered 16 consecutive quarters in the black. He did so while handling many day-to-day duties in the manner of a chief operating officer, advancing the company&#39;s growth goals by lowering production costs and chasing efficiency.</p><p> The former McKinsey analyst made a fortune during his career at Tesla, which compensated him largely in equity whose value soared through his tenure.</p><p> During his time as CFO, Kirkhorn sold roughly $49 million worth of Tesla stock, according to Equilar. He still holds more than $550 million worth of shares and stock options that have vested but not yet been exercised.</p><p> In a securities filing, Tesla thanked Kirkhorn for his “significant contributions” to the company and said he would continue with the automaker through the end of the year to support a “seamless transition.”</p><p> Hours after the announcement, Musk, in a post on X, added his gratitude, writing: “Much appreciated and best wishes for the next stage of his career.”</p><p>根据塔内贾的 LinkedIn 简历，45 岁的塔内贾自 2016 年 3 月加入 SolarCity 担任会计业务副总裁以来，一直进入马斯克的商业轨道。</p><p>在特斯拉成功收购太阳能公司后，他留在了特斯拉，马斯克还担任董事长，并于 2017 年成为公司助理财务总监，并随着时间的推移承担了更大的责任。此前，他在印度和加利福尼亚州圣何塞的普华永道会计师事务所工作了近 17 年。</p><p>特斯拉、柯克霍恩和塔内贾没有立即回应置评请求。</p><p>柯克霍恩在 LinkedIn 上发帖感谢马斯克的领导力和乐观精神。</p><p> “成为这家公司的一员是一种特殊的经历，我对自 13 年前加入以来我们一起所做的工作感到非常自豪，”Kirkhorn 说。</p><p> Tesla is a markedly different company than when Kirkhorn <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/elon-musks-surprise-pick-for-tesla-cfo-is-a-relative-unknown-11548935508?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">took the reins as CFO</a> after a surprise announcement in early 2019 that he was replacing longtime Musk confidant Deepak Ahuja.</p><p> At the time, Tesla was struggling to make the transition from niche automaker into the mainstream with its Model 3, which <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/tesla-model-3-arrives-as-elon-musk-tries-to-manage-expectations-1501234208?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none" rel="noreferrer noopener">launched in 2017</a> .</p><p> In the years that followed, the eventual success of the Model 3 and its offshoot, the Model Y crossover, would help remake Tesla. During that period, Kirkhorn worked to open Tesla&#39;s first overseas assembly factory in China and navigate supply challenges during the pandemic. Also under his tenure, Tesla&#39;s relationship with Wall Street changed as it became the largest company to join the S&amp;P 500, the most widely tracked broad stock-market benchmark.</p><p> In 2020, Tesla became the world&#39;s most valuable automaker and, in 2021, the first car company to be valued at more than $1 trillion.</p><p> Tesla&#39;s share price has since retreated, especially amid concern late last year that Musk was distracted with X and that Tesla faced a tougher competitive market with new EV rivals and higher interest rates that made selling new vehicles harder.</p><p> In the past year, Kirkhorn had taken on a more visible role.他是三月份投资者聚会的司仪，会上特斯拉重点介绍了在马斯克手下工作的高管。</p><p>与科克霍恩共事过的人称赞他能够与马斯克进行有效的联系和沟通，而自特斯拉成立之初以来，其他高管一直在努力掌握这些技能。</p><p> The relationship between the two executives echoed the dynamic between <a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/AAPL" class="company-name">Apple</a> CEO Tim Cook with his predecessor, Steve Jobs, the Journal reported.</p><p> This year has also seen the rise of another longtime Tesla executive into a bigger <strong>&nbsp;</strong> operational role. In April, Tom Zhu, who had overseen China operations, was officially made senior vice president of automotive, effectively putting him in a role overseeing factories and sales globally.</p><p class="articleTagLine"> ——威尔·福尔 (Will Feuer) 对本文做出了贡献。</p><p>写信给丽贝卡·埃利奥特（Rebecca Elliott）： <a href="mailto:rebecca.elliott@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">rebecca.elliott@wsj.com</a></p></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Mon, 07 Aug 2023 21:56:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/tesla-finance-chief-zach-kirkhorn-steps-down-44e00ad</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/tesla-finance-chief-zach-kirkhorn-steps-down-44e00ad<author><![CDATA[Rebecca Elliott]]></author><category> WSJ公司</category><category>机动车</category><category>替代燃料汽车</category><category>汽车</category><category>管理</category><category>管理层变动</category><category>企业/行业新闻</category><category>高层管理人员</category><category>内容类型</category><category>法激活过滤器</category><category>C&amp;E 行政新闻过滤器</category><category>会展行业新闻过滤器</category><category>SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category>特斯拉</category><category>特斯拉</category><category>瓦伊巴夫·塔内贾</category><category>扎克·柯克霍恩</category><category>埃隆·马斯克</category><category>管理</category><category>管理举措</category><category>公司的</category><category>行业新闻</category><category>高层管理人员</category><category>内容类型</category><category>法蒂瓦过滤器</category><category>C&amp;E 行政新闻过滤器</category><category>会展行业新闻过滤器</category><category>机动车</category><category>替代燃料汽车</category><category>汽车</category></item><item><title><![CDATA[These Headphones Stay Outside Your Ears—and Can Go for a Swim]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div> These pairs stay put while logging laps, because of tech called bone conduction <!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001105109"><div class="is-lead-inset"><div class="media-object scope-
          header
"><figure class="media-object-image img-header"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="860" height="648" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-828383?width=860&amp;height=648" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> Nicole tested waterproof headphones, including H2O Audio&#39;s Tri Pro, pictured here, in the pool and open water.</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: Will Marquardt </p></figcaption></figure></div></div></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001105109"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="columnist_mini"> <a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/nicole-nguyen"><img width="45" height="45" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-735934/AM" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></a></div><div class="byline"> By <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/nicole-nguyen" itemprop="url" rel="author">Nicole Nguyen</a></span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1">更新于 2023 年 8 月 7 日中午 12:59（美国东部时间） </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/the-best-waterproof-headphones-for-swimming-and-sweating-6a79c488"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><p> Until this summer, I never took music into the pool.</p><p> Even though tunes keep me going at work or working out, there just haven&#39;t been many great waterproof headphones or ways to get music on them since Bluetooth doesn&#39;t work well underwater.</p><p> But following recent advancements in both waterproofing and audio tech, I decided to try some out while training for a swim race. My favorite pairs ended up remaining on my head, even when I was on dry land.</p><p> If you live in a rainy area or just sweat a lot, waterproof headphones are likely to last longer than any just labeled water- <em>resistant</em> . Because of their newfangled open-ear design, they&#39;re safer to wear while running or doing other activities that also require you to pay attention to your surroundings. The design makes them more comfortable for people who experience ear pain or a suction feeling from in-ear buds.</p><p> The three models I tested use bone conduction to transmit audio:</p><ul class="articleList"><li> H2O Audio Tri Pro</li><li> Shokz OpenSwim</li><li> Naenka Runner Diver 2</li></ul><p> They look similar, with a stiff band that goes behind your neck, supporting two vibrating nodes that sit just below your temples. You don&#39;t jam anything in your ears—these headphones transmit sound through bone vibrations and wrap around your ear. The sound is less detailed, as you might imagine, but it&#39;s fine for listening during activities. Plus, you don&#39;t have to deal with any gross gunk on the ear tips.</p><p> Here&#39;s what it&#39;s like to wear the headphones underwater, and why they aren&#39;t just for swimming.</p><h3> Swim test</h3><p> Typical headphones and earbuds emit sound waves that travel into your ear canal. Earbuds are popular for working out because they&#39;re lightweight. I&#39;ve tried swimmer&#39;s earbuds in the past, and found that they tend to loosen and fall out with a lot of movement in the water. </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          inline
"><iframe width="300" height="300" src="https://graphics.wsj.com/dynamic-inset-iframer/?url=https://asset.wsj.net/wsjnewsgraphics/projects/narrator/bddba16f-f3c1-4411-a3a8-52a6ecbcdd9f.json" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe></div><p> Since bone-conducting headphones aren&#39;t in your ears, they tend to stay put when swimming. They also sound better in water when they sit tight against your skin. Swim caps aren&#39;t a nuisance here—they actually offer a nice compression and keep the headphones in place.</p><p> The headphones also come with swimming ear plugs to keep sloshing water from literally drowning out the music, though any preferred plugs will do. (I prefer silicone putty.)</p><div class="media-object scope-web
          wrap
"><div class="media-object-rich-text"><h4>分享你的意见</h4><p><em>What tech do you use while swimming or doing water sports?加入下面的对话。</em></p></div></div><p> Since Bluetooth has very short range underwater, most swimming headphones require you to load MP3 files onto the device via a USB connection to your computer. You can drag and drop music files or audiobooks you own. (I download free podcasts at <a href="https://podcastindex.org/" target="_blank" class="icon none">podcastindex.org</a> .) The headphones all worked great: The background music kept my tempo up, lap after lap.</p><p> On land, without any ear plugs of course, your ears are open to the world&#39;s sounds. Awareness of car honks, shuffling pedestrians and other environmental noises is a plus for running and cycling. At home, these bone-conduction headphones can help you keep an ear on the kids without missing a podcast.</p><p> There are drawbacks to the open-ear style. Bone-conducting headphones don&#39;t match the sound quality of top headphones and earbuds. And in very noisy urban environments, you&#39;ll have to turn the volume way up.</p><h3> The best aquatic beats</h3><p> H2O Audio&#39;s <a href="https://h2oaudio.com/collections/frontpage/products/tri-pro-multi-sport-headphones-with-playlist" target="_blank" class="icon none">Tri Pro</a> ($179) is among the newest waterproof options, and it&#39;s the most versatile swim-friendly headset I&#39;ve tried. </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="466" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-828991?width=700&amp;height=466" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> H2O Audio&#39;s Tri Pro headphones let you listen to music from streaming platforms underwater. But there&#39;s a caveat.</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: H2O Audio</p></figcaption></figure></div><p> It has Bluetooth connectivity for dry-land workouts, and 8 gigabytes of internal memory for playing media underwater. The Tri Pro is notable because of a new feature called Playlist+, which allows you to play back content from streaming platforms.虽然该设备上没有其他防水耳机提供这种功能，但需要注意的是，您必须在锻炼之前记录该内容。 （ <a href="https://shopzygo.com/" target="_blank" class="icon none" rel="noopener">Zygo 的耳机</a>，299 美元， <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/4-ways-to-become-a-better-swimmerfrom-smart-goggles-to-waterproof-headphones-11622141542?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">可以将蓝牙信号转变</a>为适合水的射频，但你的手机需要靠近泳池边缘，这可能不适用于公共区域。）</p><p> With the headset connected via Bluetooth to H2O Audio&#39;s smartphone app, you play media tracks on your phone. The app records and transfers them to the Tri Pro. You can set a timer, so it can happen overnight while the headset charges. Content is saved as one long file, though, so you can&#39;t skip tracks. H2O Audio says <a href="https://h2oaudio.com/pages/legal-copyright" target="_blank" class="icon none">copying these files is legal</a> since it&#39;s only for personal use.</p><p> Sound like a hassle? An optional clip accessory can hold an <a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/AAPL" class="company-name">Apple</a> Watch at the back of your goggles, so you can listen to downloaded music from Spotify or another streaming app via Bluetooth. (The watch can&#39;t be on your wrist, because the range underwater is only a couple of inches.)</p><p> The battery takes about an hour to charge fully and lasts five hours. The headphones are rated as waterproof down to 12 feet deep for an unlimited amount of time—better than most competitors. I do wish Tri Pro came with a protective case. The neck band can break if bent, so it isn&#39;t a good idea to throw it in a gym bag unprotected. </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          inline
"><iframe width="300" height="300" src="https://graphics.wsj.com/dynamic-inset-iframer/?url=https://asset.wsj.net/wsjnewsgraphics/projects/narrator/42cd4ef1-0382-40bb-b1d8-8e43c3de8200.json" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe></div><p> The Shokz <a href="https://shokz.com/products/openswim" target="_blank" class="icon none">OpenSwim</a> ($150) headphones weren&#39;t as full-featured but they fit my head best. They have an eight-hour battery life and come with a handy case—but no Bluetooth. If you&#39;re looking for a lightweight, phone-free set, and don&#39;t mind loading up MP3s, go with the OpenSwim.</p><p> If you want a really long-lasting battery and the ability to load up a lot of media including storage-hogging audiobooks, Naenka&#39;s <a href="https://www.naenka.com/products/runner-diver2-bone-conduction-headphones-for-sports" target="_blank" class="icon none">Runner Diver2</a> ($190) is a good pick. The headset wasn&#39;t my top choice because it was bulkier and heavier than the other two, but it offers a relatively massive 32GB of memory and 10 hours of battery life, as well as Bluetooth connectivity.</p><p> With these headphones on, I swam longer and faster. I didn&#39;t win my race, but pool training just got a lot more fun.</p><p> — <em>For more WSJ Technology analysis, reviews, advice and headlines,</em> <a href="https://www.wsj.com/newsletters?sub=55&amp;mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none"><em>sign up for our weekly newsletter</em></a> <em>.</em></p><p> Write to Nicole Nguyen at <a href="mailto:nicole.nguyen@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">nicole.nguyen@wsj.com</a> </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          inline
"><iframe width="300" height="300" src="https://graphics.wsj.com/dynamic-inset-iframer/?url=https://asset.wsj.net/wsjnewsgraphics/projects/narrator/cdf3741a-b32c-4964-a79a-63023038548a.json" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe></div></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Mon, 07 Aug 2023 16:59:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/the-best-waterproof-headphones-for-swimming-and-sweating-6a79c488</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/the-best-waterproof-headphones-for-swimming-and-sweating-6a79c488<author><![CDATA[Nicole Nguyen]]></author><category> wsjlifework</category><category>计算机/消费电子产品</category><category>个人电子产品</category><category>消费类电子产品</category><category>技术</category><category>Wearable Technology</category><category> Aquatics/Water Sports</category><category>政治/一般新闻</category><category>艺术/娱乐</category><category>身体/心理健康</category><category>健康</category><category>生活/生活方式</category><category>Music</category><category>个人技术</category><category>运动的</category><category>内容类型</category><category>法激活过滤器</category><category>C&amp;E 排除过滤器</category><category>日常新闻</category><category>SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category> aquatics</category><category> water sports</category><category>政治的</category><category>一般新闻</category><category>艺术</category><category>娱乐</category><category>身体的</category><category>心理健康</category><category>health</category><category>活的</category><category>生活方式</category><category>music</category><category>个人技术</category><category>sports</category><category>内容类型</category><category>法蒂瓦过滤器</category><category>c&amp;e 排除过滤器</category><category>常规新闻</category><category>电脑</category><category>消费类电子产品</category><category>个人电子产品</category><category>技术</category><category>wearable technology </category></item><item><title><![CDATA[AI Set to Upend the Talent Search at Ad Agencies and Brands]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div>生成式人工智能可以帮助招聘人员找到更多样化、更专业的候选人，但求职者也用它来润色自己的简历<!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001111748"><div class="is-lead-inset"><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-header"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="466" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-830228?width=700&amp;height=466" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">一屏 ChatGPT 回复。招聘人员表示，生成式人工智能可以增强雇主为特定工作寻找最佳候选人的能力。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：Jaap Arriens/Zuma Press </p></figcaption></figure></div></div></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001111748"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline"> <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/patrick-coffee" itemprop="url" rel="author">帕特里克·咖啡</a></span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1">美国东部时间 2023 年 8 月 7 日上午 6:00 </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/ai-set-to-upend-the-talent-search-at-ad-agencies-and-brands-cf9df34f"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><p>正如生成式人工智能似乎即将<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/ai-advertising-industry-tools-risks-f880420a?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">改变营销人员的日常工作</a>一样，它也可能会颠覆招聘人员的工作，以找到合适的人选。</p><p>招聘人员表示，这项技术一方面可以帮助品牌和广告公司更有效地确定求职目标，但另一方面，它将使简历的分类变得更加困难，因为更多的简历本身就是人工智能的产品。</p><p>二十多年来，招聘人员一直在使用所谓的机器学习人工智能，主要以软件的形式使用职位描述来自动过滤申请人库。然而，招聘人员认为，生成式人工智能的出现将增强他们为特定工作寻找最佳候选人的能力。</p><p>广告控股公司<a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/WPP" class="">WPP</a>人才招聘和猎头全球主管 Shannon Moorman 表示：“我已经这样做很长时间了，这可能是我见过的最关键的、会扰乱招聘的事情<span class="company-name-type">。</span> ”</p><p>摩尔曼说，人工智能对营销组织特别有帮助，这些组织经常进行复杂的搜索，旨在预测候选人的未来表现以及他们的直接经验。 </p><div class="media-object scope-
          wrap
"><figure class="media-object-image img-wrap"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="639" height="426" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-830250?width=639&amp;height=426" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> Bard，谷歌的人工智能入口。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：Nikos Pekiaridis/Zuma Press</p></figcaption></figure></div><p> ChatGPT 和 Google 的 Bard 等工具最直接的用途在于自动化部分重复性任务：向候选人写直接消息并创建职位列表大纲。在这两种情况下，人工智能生成的内容都可以由人类定制，以更好地描述营销人员越来越寻求的高度专业化和以技术为中心的角色。</p><p>广告公司 Goodby Silverstein &amp; Partners 的副合伙人兼人才总监扎克·坎菲尔德 (Zach Canfield) 表示，ChatGPT“可能会为你提供 40% 的大纲，然后你必须对其进行真正的微调”。坎菲尔德表示，生成式人工智能带来的效率提升为该机构腾出了更多时间来寻找和瞄准创意专业人士，例如那些在人工智能、虚拟现实和相关技术方面拥有经验的人。</p><p>营销人员经常寻找国际候选人来担任顶级创意职位。对于他们来说，生成式人工智能可以总结美国移民法所需的复杂法律文件，并帮助招聘人员与这些候选人更流畅地沟通。</p><p> “对于候选人来说，这是一条双向路。有时我的西班牙语比他们的英语强，所以我确实相信 [AI] 会带来一些安慰和可信度，并在双方之间建立融洽的关系，”经常使用 Bard 和其他人工智能工具的创意招聘公司 Sasha the Mensch 总裁 Sasha Martens 说道。例如翻译 DeepL，在美国境外招聘时更确定地使用当地俚语</p><h3>弹奏弦乐</h3><p>然而，生成式人工智能对营销招聘人员最引人注目的用途可能在于它能够简化流程，例如创建所谓的布尔字符串，这是一系列“如果、那么和”提示，用于更准确地定位候选人，莫尔曼说。</p><p> Moorman 表示，过去，WPP 招聘人员可能会花费数小时编写数百个字符串，以便在湾区寻找具有 JavaScript 编码语言专业知识的软件开发人员。现在，生成式人工智能已经自动化了大部分工作，创建布尔字符串来找到符合招聘人员目标的候选人，有时会建议招聘人员没有明确要求的更精确的目标关键词。</p><p>莫尔曼说，招聘人员还可以利用人工智能从现有的职位描述中提取一组关键词，使用这些术语创建一个新的字符串并进一步细化搜索结果。</p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          wrap
"></div><p> Moorman 表示，当与 HireEZ 等机器学习工具相结合时，生成式人工智能可以打开搜索范围，包括 Reddit 子社区、开发者论坛和历史悠久的黑人学院和大学的校友团体等在线圈子。她说，WPP 这样就可以更快地从更广泛的候选人群体中进行选拔。</p><p> “人工智能让我兴奋的一件事是，它实际上将为我们打开多样化人才库的大门，否则我们甚至不会意识到这一点，”莫尔曼说。</p><p>她说，如果使用得当，生成人工智能还可以减少偏见，例如帮助识别职位描述中可能会阻止女性申请的男性倾向术语。 （WPP 发言人表示，其中包括“驱动”、“客观”和“坚定”。）剔除此类线索的能力对于那些经常难以实现自身多元化招聘目标的营销组织来说可能很有用。</p><p>坎菲尔德说，富有创意的招聘人员根据候选人工作的公认质量（而不是他们的技术专长）进行搜索，也可能会发现人工智能对于研究目的很有价值。例如，如果 Goodby Silverstein &amp; Partners 想要瞄准近年来最受欢迎的汽车品牌活动背后的思想家，招聘人员可以使用 ChatGPT 提示来收集在行业颁奖典礼上名列前茅的更全面的工作清单，包括他们的例子他说，可能已经忘记或以前没有见过。</p><p>人工智能“并没有改变我的申请者工作流程，但它改变了我的能力，让我能够更好地主动寻找那些我想主动追求的人，”坎菲尔德说。</p><h3><strong>准确性尚未保证</strong></h3><p>但麦肯锡合伙人布莱恩·汉考克表示，人工智能加速招聘的最大障碍仍然是其制造虚假信息的倾向。</p><p>汉考克说：“当你在做背景调查或准备面试时，它可能会对候选人产生一些影响。” </p><div class="media-object scope-
          wrap
"><figure class="media-object-image img-wrap"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="639" height="426" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-830254?width=639&amp;height=426" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> LinkedIn 今年开始为用户提供人工智能工具，让他们的简历更受欢迎。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：Jaap Arriens/Zuma Press</p></figcaption></figure></div><p>例如，当汉考克要求一个所谓的大型语言模型工具来总结他自己的传记时，它告诉他，他毕业于康奈尔大学工业与劳动关系学院；事实上，他就读于弗吉尼亚大学。</p><p>招聘公司 CPS 的高级合伙人兼 AI 创始人 David J. Schueneman 表示，许多高管招聘人员尚未完全接受人工智能，但他们面临着来自已经接受人工智能的竞争对手的压力，以及越来越多渴望向他们出售相关产品的供应商的压力。其营销专业部门ad+one。</p><p>具有讽刺意味的是，所有这些自动化意味着招聘人员正在尝到<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/ai-isnt-coming-for-marketers-jobsnot-yet-at-least-3bc18750?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">一些营销专业人士已经感受到的</a>对工作保障的焦虑。舒内曼表示，这种担忧与二十年前 LinkedIn 等在线求职论坛和平台的兴起所引起的恐慌相呼应。</p><p>他说，这些担忧可能是没有根据的，因为招聘最终依赖于人与人之间的互动。他说，随着人工智能变得越来越流行，进而变得更加商品化，它对招聘人员的竞争优势将会消失，因为“人工智能驱动”等短语的无处不在使得它们几乎毫无意义。</p><div class="media-object scope-web
          wrap
"><div class="media-object-rich-text"><h4>分享你的意见</h4><p><em>您认为人工智能技术将如何改变招聘流程？加入下面的对话。</em></p></div></div><p>求职者自己对人工智能工具包的了解使招聘人员的流程进一步复杂化，在某些方面加强了人工密切关注的必要性。</p><p>一些人工智能工具，比如 LinkedIn 今年发布的工具，是专门为帮助申请人填写个人资料而设计的。全球招聘网络 (Global Recruiters Network) 的业务开发经理约翰·罗腾堡 (John Rothenburg) 表示，它们的受欢迎程度意味着招聘人员现在面临着大量类似的简历，其中充满了所有最热门的关键词。全球招聘网络是一家将求职者与各行业公司联系起来的公司。</p><p> “突然之间，每个候选人都成为了一名优秀的作家，”罗腾堡说。 “他们将自己定位为 A 级玩家，但实际上他们是 B 级玩家或 C 级玩家。”</p><p> “我们的招聘人员需要整理更多的噪音，”他说。</p><p>写信给 Patrick Coffee <a href="mailto:patrick.coffee@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">patrick.coffee@wsj.com</a></p></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Mon, 07 Aug 2023 10:00:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/ai-set-to-upend-the-talent-search-at-ad-agcies-and-brands-cf9df34f</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/ai-set-to-upend-the-talent-search-at-ad-agcies-and-brands-cf9df34f<author><![CDATA[Patrick Coffee]]></author><category> Artificial Intelligence Technologies</category><category>广告服务</category><category>广告/营销/公共关系</category><category>商业/消费者服务</category><category>营销服务</category><category>技术</category><category>Artificial Intelligence/Machine Learning</category><category>政治/一般新闻</category><category>职业规划/管理</category><category>Computer Science</category><category>一般劳工问题</category><category>求职</category><category>Sciences/Humanities</category><category> SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category> artificial intelligence</category><category> machine learning</category><category>政治的</category><category>一般新闻</category><category>职业生涯规划</category><category>管理</category><category>computer science</category><category>一般劳工问题</category><category>求职</category><category>sciences</category><category> humanities</category><category> artificial intelligence technologies</category><category>广告服务</category><category>广告</category><category>营销</category><category>公共关系</category><category>商业</category><category>消费服务</category><category>营销服务</category><category>技术</category></item><item><title><![CDATA[A Real-Estate Haven Turns Perilous With $1 Trillion Coming Due]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div>公寓楼的价值多年来一直上涨，但飙升的利率现在笼罩着该行业的业主<figure><img src="https://images.wsj.net/im-830485/?width=1278&amp;size=1" alt="随着租金稳步上涨，投资者抬高了多户住宅的价格。" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"><figcaption>随着租金稳步上涨，投资者抬高了多户住宅的价格。理查德·B·莱文/祖玛出版社<span>理查德·B·莱文/祖玛出版社</span></figcaption></figure><!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001112088"></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001112088"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline">作者： <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/konrad-putzier" itemprop="url" rel="author">康拉德·普齐尔</a></span>和<span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/will-parker" itemprop="url" rel="author">威尔·帕克</a></span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1">美国东部时间 2023 年 8 月 7 日上午 5:30 </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/a-real-estate-haven-turns-perilous-with-roughly-1-trillion-coming-due-74d20528"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          bigtophero
"></div><p>长期以来被认为是房地产天堂的公寓楼正在成为陷入困境的商业地产领域的<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/houston-apartment-owner-loses-3-200-units-to-foreclosure-as-multifamily-feels-the-heat-fb3d0e75?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">下一个主要麻烦点</a>。</p><p>多年来，受租金稳步上涨和巨额回报前景的吸引，投资者不断抬高多户住宅的价格。许多人承担了过多的债务，期望能够以足够快的速度提高租金来偿还债务。</p><p>与受到远程工作和电子商务严重打击的写字楼和商场不同，出租公寓的空置率较低。公寓行业的主要问题不是缺乏需求——自 2020 年以来租金飙升——而是<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/investors-bet-that-high-rates-will-linger-61cdaeb7?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">利率</a>。</p><p>去年债务成本的突然飙升现在有可能使全国许多多户家庭业主破产。数据公司<a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/CSGP" class="">CoStar</a>的数据显示，继去年上涨 25% 后，截至 6 月份的一年中，公寓楼价值下降了 14% <span class="company-name-type">。</span>这一下降幅度与写字楼价值的下降幅度大致相同。 </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="467" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-830530?width=700&amp;height=467" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">许多公寓楼投资者承担了过多的债务，期望他们能够足够快地提高租金来偿还债务。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：大卫·保罗·莫里斯/彭博新闻</p></figcaption></figure></div><p>多户住宅类别的抵押贷款拖欠率较低，但仍在增加。借贷成本翻了一番，租金增长放缓，建筑费用上升。数据提供商特雷普今年早些时候发现，在面临违约风险的商业抵押贷款中，一类出租公寓债务占很大比例。</p><p> Apartment landlords face a “hydrogen-bomb scenario,” said Peter Sotoloff, a veteran real-estate finance executive, a former founding member of Blackstone&#39;s property debt business and former managing partner at Mack Real Estate Credit Strategies.<br><br>根据抵押贷款银行家协会的数据，未偿还的多户抵押贷款在过去十年中增加了一倍多，达到约 2 万亿美元。特雷普表示，这几乎是办公室债务的两倍。该数据提供商补充说，9807 亿美元的多户家庭债务预计将在 2023 年至 2027 年间到期。 </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          wrap
"><img width="600" height="800" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-830785?width=600" alt="不明确的" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><p> “每个人都专注于办公室，”索托洛夫说。他补充说，公寓违约的风险“是一个非常大的问题，但没有得到应有的关注。”</p><p>洛杉矶、休斯顿和旧金山的多户住宅业主拖欠了数千套公寓的贷款。 <a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/BX" class="">Blackstone</a> <span class="company-name-type">,</span> the world&#39;s largest alternative-asset manager, is in special servicing on mortgages related to 11 Manhattan apartment buildings, according to a person familiar with the matter. Blackstone 的一位发言人表示，这些建筑存在独特的问题，“不能代表我们在更广泛的租赁住房组合中看到的实力。”</p><p>公寓楼被誉为风险较低的商业房地产投资。即使在经济衰退时期，包括2008-2009年金融危机期间房地产市场崩溃时，它们的表现也相对较好。人们总是需要一个地方居住，在危机时期，前房主会涌入租赁市场。</p><p>通货膨胀还使房东能够比平时提高租金，从而推高了其建筑物的价值。根据租赁网站 Apartment List 的数据，2021 年至 2022 年 18 个月内，租金要价上涨了 25%。 </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><div class="media-object-video"><div class="wsj-media-summary clearfix"><div class="strap-container"><h4 class="strap" itemprop="description"></h4></div></div><iframe width="400" height="225" src="https://video-api.wsj.com/api-video/player/v3/iframe.html?guid=88CDF171-D046-4FD4-A4BB-72130DCCB4C6&amp;height=225&amp;width=400&amp;plid=video_amp&amp;chainVideos=true&amp;parentUrl=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.wsj.com%2Famp%2Farticles%2Fa-real-estate-haven-turns-perilous-with-roughly-1-trillion-coming-due-74d20528&amp;a=a" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe><p class="imageCaption">由于住房供应短缺，开发商正在将更多空置办公室改造成公寓。但并非所有建筑物都适合重复利用，尽管美国各地有超过 10 亿平方英尺的办公空间闲置 图片插图：Amber Bragdon<span class="imageCredit">
        
        
        </span></p></div></div><p>对于许多投资者来说，这些因素<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/rising-interest-rates-concern-apartment-building-owners-renters-11653393600?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">证明支付高价是合理的</a>。公寓楼业主通常从债券市场借入超过 80% 的建筑价值。大多数公寓贷款都是固定利率的长期抵押贷款。然而，在疫情期间，投资者获得了更多<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/bonds-backed-by-apartments-are-under-stress-as-housing-market-cools-9717d617?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">短期浮动利率贷款</a>。</p><p>许多投资者大幅提高租金，押注一旦他们的建筑物产生更高的租金收入，他们就可以以更高的估值出售建筑物或为债务再融资。</p><p>但很少有人预料到利率会上升得如此之快，从而压低建筑价值并迫使房东以更高的利率进行再融资。作为重要资金来源的地区性银行如今的放贷量大幅减少，导致抵押贷款再融资变得更加困难。美国许多城市<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/renters-are-about-to-get-the-upper-hand-f6387df4?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">的租金增长大幅放缓</a><a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/renters-are-about-to-get-the-upper-hand-f6387df4?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">，</a>而通货膨胀和保险费上涨则提高了建筑物的运营成本。 </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          wrap
"><img width="600" height="800" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-830093?width=600" alt="不明确的" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><p>主要由浮动利率债务和小投资者现金资助的一批新的私人房地产公司已成为多户住宅市场上更大的竞争对手。一些人基于对未来几年租金大幅上涨的乐观预期而支付了更高的价格。现在，他们在使数字发挥作用方面遇到了困难。</p><p>总部位于洛杉矶的 Tides Equities 自 2016 年以来已收购了价值超过 65 亿美元的租赁房产，其中大部分是西南部城市的中低收入公寓楼。评级机构报告显示，2021 年，该公司预计达拉斯郊区的一处房产的租金将在三年内上涨 44%。<br><br> 6 月，Tides 告诉投资者，该战略并未按计划进行。该公司在一封信中表示，租户“现金变得过于紧张”。信中称，一些房产不再赚取足够的钱来偿还债务，投资者可能需要投入更多资金来挽救建筑物免于违约。</p><p> Tides 联合创始人 Sean Kia 和 Ryan Andrade 在接受采访时表示，他们正在与贷方合作，寻找避免面临困难的房产违约的方法。</p><p>总部位于休斯敦的 Nitya Capital 拥有价值约 30 亿美元的多户住宅，该公司在 3 月份通知投资者，由于利率上升，该公司将大幅削减利润预期。</p><p> Nitya 首席执行官 Swapnil Agarwal 在一封投资者信中写道：“我们实际上是在支付更高的抵押贷款成本，而不是进行现金分配。”</p><p>公寓业主仍有理由保持乐观。即使银行撤退，<a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/FNMA" class="company-name">房利美</a>和<a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/FMCC" class="company-name">房地美</a>仍能提供政府支持的可靠贷款来源。大多数分析师预计住房短缺和高租金将持续存在。如果利率下降，房地产价格可能会迅速反弹。拥有固定利率抵押贷款的多户家庭业主更有能力度过任何近期的动荡。</p><div class="media-object scope-web
          wrap
"><div class="media-object-rich-text"><h4>分享你的意见</h4><p><em>您对商业地产的前景如何？加入下面的对话。</em></p></div></div><p>尽管如此，其他威胁仍在加剧。今年和明年开业的新公寓楼数量异常多，特别是在高端租赁市场，引起了供应方面的担忧。</p><p> CoStar资本市场分析全国总监查德·利特尔(Chad Littell)表示，此外，公寓楼价值比商业楼宇价值更容易受到利率上涨的影响，因为它们与10年期国债价格密切相关，而随着利率上升，十年期国债价格暴跌。</p><p>即使是一些经历过风暴的资深房地产投资者也显得很脆弱。旧金山最大的房东之一<a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/NZ/XNZE/GSH" class="">Veritas Investments</a><span class="company-name-type">及其</span>合作伙伴在过去一年中拖欠了 95 栋出租建筑的债务。结果，该公司将损失超过三分之一的旧金山投资组合。</p><p>该公司今年早些时候表示，“多户型房地产行业正面临着许多与其他资产类别（包括办公楼、零售业和酒店业）相同的财务挑战。”</p><p>写信给 Konrad Putzier <a href="mailto:konrad.putzier@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">（konrad.putzier@wsj.com）</a>和 Will Parker（ <a href="mailto:will.parker@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">will.parker@wsj.com</a> ）</p><p id="correction" class="correction"> <strong>Corrections &amp; Amplifications</strong><br> Blackstone&#39;s portfolio of 11 Manhattan apartment buildings is in special servicing. A previous version of this story incorrectly said they are in default. (Corrected on Aug. 7)</p></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Mon, 07 Aug 2023 09:30:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/a-real-estate-haven-turns-perilous-with-roughly-1-trillion-coming-due-74d20528</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/a-real-estate-haven-turns-perilous-with-roughly-1-trillion-coming-due-74d20528<author><![CDATA[Konrad PutzierWill Parker]]></author><category>住房</category><category>商业地产</category><category>企业/行业新闻</category><category>住房</category><category>商业房地产</category><category>SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category>黑色的石头</category><category>巴克斯</category><category>房利美</category><category>国家气象局</category><category>房地美</category><category>FMCC</category><category>科星集团</category><category>CSGP</category><category>良好的精神好客</category><category>谷胱甘肽新西兰</category><category>新西兰：还原型谷胱甘肽</category><category>彼得·索托洛夫</category><category>肖恩·基亚</